aWFRuleDesc.RuleText:
; aWF_RT_Formule (aWLIClaimRuleEngineWithCashValue) (Def Version:2) (Implem Version:1)
uses aWFRuleDesc, WFTypes
function MortalityTable(Age : Int4) return Num8 uses aWFStandAloneRule
var tmpRule : aWFRuleDesc
tmpRule = self.GetExactRuleToExecuteFromRankInRuleDesc(0, self.CurrentDate) if tmpRule <> Nil aWFStandAloneRule(tmpRule.MyOwner).AppendParam(Age, 0, tmpRule) tmpRule.GetStandAloneResult(_Result, self) aWFStandAloneRule(tmpRule.MyOwner).CleanParamsAfterExecution(tmpRule) else self.AppendComment('No rule version defined at this date') endIf endFunc
procedure WFCalculate(inOut Result : tWFAmount) ; The annual premium is based on the mortality table and the chosen coverage amount Result = 2.5 * (100 - self.MortalityTable(self.Subscriber__Age__At_Subscription)) Result = Result * self.Option__CoverageAmount / 1000 endProc

aWFStandAloneTable.Name: MortalityTable

aWFRuleDesc.Name: APC

aWFRuleDesc.RuleText:
; aWF_RT_Formule (aWLIClaimRuleEngineWithCashValue) (Def Version:1) (Implem Version:1)
uses WFTypes
procedure WFCalculate(inOut Result : tWFAmount) Result = self.Option__PaidUpPremiumAmount + self.Option__AnnualPremiumAmount * self.Option__AgeInYears * (1 - self.Option__SurrenderChargePercentage) endProc
aWFRuleDesc.Name: TCV

aWFRuleDesc.RuleText:
; aWF_RT_Formule (aWLIClaimRuleEngineWithCashValue) (Def Version:1) (Implem Version:1)
uses WFTypes, aWLICoverageAmountAndPremiumVersion
procedure WFCalculate(inOut Result : tWFNum8) var Choice : tWFAmount var initialDate : tWFDate
if (self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvSubscription) or (self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvEndorsement) Choice = 50000 self.AppendPossibleValue(Choice) Choice = 100000 self.AppendPossibleValue(Choice) Choice = 150000 self.AppendPossibleValue(Choice) Choice = 200000 self.AppendPossibleValue(Choice) elseif self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvReduction initialDate = self.Option__SubscriptionDate self.IncYears(8, initialDate) Result = self.Option__CoverageAmountAtDate(self.CurrentDate - 1) * (self.CurrentDate - self.Option__SubscriptionDate) / (initialDate - self.Option__SubscriptionDate) elseif self.Option__CashValueStatus = cvPaidUpConversion Result = self.Option__CoverageAmount endIf endProc
aWFRuleDesc.Name: Eligibility Rule

; aWF_RT_Formule (aWLIClaimRuleEngineWithCashValue) (Def Version:1) (Implem Version:1)
procedure WFCalculate(inOut Result : Boolean) Result = self.Option__NbLoans < 8 if not Result self.AppendErrorMessage('You can not have more than 8 loans') else Result = self.Option__TotalLoanAmount + self.DeliveredService__RequestedLoanAmount < 0.8 * self.Option__TabularCashValue if not Result if not Result self.AppendErrorMessage('You can not withdraw more than 80% of your TCV') endIf endIf endIf endProc

aWLIOfferedIndividualLifeCoverageWithCas.Description: {\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033\deflangfe1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fswiss\fprq2\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}} {\colortbl ;\red153\green51\blue0;} \viewkind4\uc1\pard\nowidctlpar\lang2057\f0\fs16 Permanent life insurance coverage for as long as you live and continue to make timely premium payments.\par With level premiums and the accumulation of cash values, whole life insurance is a good choice for long-range goals. The guaranteed cash values can provide money later on to help with temporary needs or emergencies.\par \par \cf1\b\fs20 Features of Whole Life Insurance\par \cf0\b0\fs16\par Premiums generally are level and payable for life: Since premiums are level, the younger you are when you purchase a whole life policy, the less expensive the annual premiums will be.\par \par \b Dividends:\b0 Whole life insurance policies can earn dividends. Dividends result when our actual life insurance costs turn out to be less than we assumed in setting our premiums. Dividends are not guaranteed, since we don't know our actual costs in advance. \par \b Guaranteed Cash Values:\b0 Unlike term life insurance, which does not accumulate any cash values, some of the money you pay into your whole life policy accumulates as guaranteed cash values. If you choose to surrender the policy, these guaranteed cash values would be available to you. Or, as long as the policy is in force, you may borrow against them as a policy loan at the current policy loan interest rate. \par \par The amount of your guaranteed cash value depends on the kind of whole life policy you have, its size and how long you have had it. The growth in cash values is tax deferred under current federal income tax law. Borrowed amounts reduce the death benefit and cash surrender value. \par \par \par }
aWLIOfferedIndividualLifeCoverageWithCas.Name: Standard Whole Life
